## 28. Mathematical Intuition: Request Cost

Suppose an API returns (p) records per page and contains (n) records.

The required number of requests is approximately:

[
\left\lceil \frac{n}{p} \right\rceil
]

For:

[
n = 1000
]

and:

[
p = 100
]

the number of requests is:

[
\frac{1000}{100} = 10
]

If every request takes (t) seconds, sequential request time is approximately:

[
T = \frac{n}{p} \times t
]

If each request takes 0.5 seconds:

[
T = 10 \times 0.5 = 5 \text{ seconds}
]

This excludes processing and network variation.

---

## 29. Time Complexity

For one response containing (n) records:

JSON parsing:

[
O(n)
]

Schema validation:

[
O(n)
]

DataFrame creation:

[
O(n)
]

Overall processing:

[
\boxed{O(n)}
]

Network time is not represented well by Big-O because it depends on latency, server performance, and response size.

Memory use is approximately:

[
\boxed{O(n)}
]

when the entire API response is loaded at once.

